agnostic trail.\n\n**Severity:** HIGH -- Misreports hook status when the config file is corrupted.\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 6 -- HIGH: `ParseHookEvent` returns `nil, nil` for unknown hook names\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/5/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/lifecycle.go`, lines 56-60\n\n**Issue:** When Copilot CLI sends a hook name that the code does not recognize (e.g., a new hook type added in a future Copilot CLI version), `ParseHookEvent` returns `nil, nil`. The caller in the framework dispatcher (`hooks_cmd.go` or the generic lifecycle dispatcher) would need to check for `nil` event *and* `nil` error, which is an easy pattern to get wrong.\n\n```go\ncase HookNamePreToolUse, HookNamePostToolUse, HookNameErrorOccurred:\n    return nil, nil //nolint:nilnil // Pass-through hooks have no lifecycle action\ndefault:\n    return nil, nil //nolint:nilnil // Unknown hooks have no lifecycle action\n```\n\nThe `//nolint:nilnil` comment acknowledges this is a code smell. The pass-through hooks (`PreToolUse`, `PostToolUse`, `ErrorOccurred`) are intentionally no-ops, but the `default` case silently drops unknown hooks. If Copilot CLI adds a new hook that carries important lifecycle information and the CLI version hasn't been updated, that data is silently lost.\n\n**User Impact:** No error or warning when an unknown hook is received. The user has no way to know that an important hook is being ignored.\n\n**Recommendation:** Log unknown hooks at debug level so there is at least a trail. The pass-through hooks are fine as-is since they are explicitly enumerated.\n\n```go\ndefault:\n    logging.Debug(ctx, \"copilot-cli: ignoring unknown hook\", \"hook\", hookName)\n    return nil, nil\n```\n\n**Severity:** HIGH -- Silent data loss for future hook types with zero diagnostic output.\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 7 -- MEDIUM: Transcript extraction functions silently skip malformed data payloads\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/5/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/transcript.go`, lines 100-131 (`extractModifiedFilesFromEvents`), lines 134-153 (`extractPromptsFromEvents`), lines 156-173 (`extractSummaryFromEvents`)\n\n**Issue:** All three functions use `json.Unmarshal(events[i].Data, &data)` with `continue` on error. This means if the Copilot CLI transcript format changes (e.g., the `data` field structure changes for `tool.execution_complete`), the code silently produces empty results instead of surfacing that the expected data could not be parsed.\n\n```go\nvar data toolExecCompleteData\nif err := json.Unmarshal(events[i].Data, &data); err != nil {\n    continue\n}\n```\n\n**Hidden Errors:** Schema changes in the Copilot CLI transcript format, corrupted data fields, unexpected null values -- all silently skipped.\n\n**User Impact:** If Copilot CLI changes its event schema, users will suddenly have empty file change lists, empty prompts, and empty summaries in their checkpoints. There will be no error message explaining why.\n\n**Recommendation:** This is a reasonable tradeoff for JSONL parsing where some events may have different shapes, but there should be at least a counter or debug log. Consider logging when 100% of events of an expected type fail to parse (that indicates a schema change, not a single corrupt event).\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM -- Acceptable for individual malformed events, but could mask a systematic format change.\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 8 -- MEDIUM: `resolveTranscriptRef` falls back to empty string on error\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/5/cmd/entire/cli/agent/copilotcli/lifecycle.go`, lines 134-141\n\n**Issue:** When `GetSessionDir` fails, the function logs a warning and returns an empty string. This empty string then becomes `event.SessionRef`, which will cause `handleLifecycleTurnEnd` to fail later with \"transcript file not specified.\" The warning log is good, but the eventual failure message (\"transcript file not specified\") will not mention that the root cause was 